The surface resistance module has already been fully ported. Here's a summary:

**Already completed:**
- `src/biogeophys/surface_resistance.jl` — Full port of `SurfaceResistanceMod.F90` (264 lines)
- `test/test_surface_resistance.jl` — Comprehensive tests (445 lines)
- `include()` entry in `src/CLM.jl` (line 72)
- `include()` entry in `test/runtests.jl` (line 52)

**What was ported:**
- `SurfaceResistanceControl` struct (method selection)
- `SurfaceResistanceParams` struct (`d_max`, `frac_sat_soil_dsl_init`)
- `soil_resistance_read_nl!` — namelist reader
- `surface_resistance_read_params!` — parameter reader
- `do_soilevap_beta()` / `do_soil_resistance_sl14()` — method query functions
- `calc_soilevap_resis!` — dispatcher
- `calc_beta_leepielke1992!` — Lee-Pielke 1992 beta factor
- `calc_soil_resistance_sl14!` — Swenson & Lawrence 2014 soil resistance

**Tests:** All 7018 tests pass, including surface resistance tests covering both methods, urban columns, wet/ice landunits, snow/surface water fractions, wet/dry soil conditions, frozen soil with ice, masked column skipping, and method dispatch.

The commit "Port Surface resistance from Fortran to Julia" already exists in the git history (commit `4676373`). No further action needed.
